# Languages as packages

This document sets the design principle for a Loom language service — the thing that gives one language its editor support inside a `.loom` file: its diagnostics, its hover, its completion. It is written before the code, and grounded in how other tools already solve language-agnostic editor support, so the design is reasoned from precedent rather than guessed. Where Loom has no precedent, the document says so and reasons from first principles instead.

_The present tense states the target. The contract here is partly built and partly ahead of the code._

The principle in one line: **a language service type-checks Products; the frame produces the de re — the composed code — as a graph of Products; the host provides the runtime.** Everything below follows from that sentence, and most of it is a known answer, borrowed from a tool that solved the same problem first.

## What a service works on: a Product

A Loom language service does not see a file. It sees a **Product**: a resolved composition root — the author's own code, fully composed — which Loom hands to the editor as one unit. Across a workspace these Products form a graph: each a vertex, the cross-file references between them the edges. The vertices are what Loom exposes to the editor; everything else is interior to them.

A Product is whole. The sections an author wrote apart — a root, and the members its anchors fold in — compose into one resolved text, and the service checks that text. A member is not a second thing the service must find and skip. It is interior to its Product, and the diagnostics, hover, and completion it earns come from the Product's analysis, mapped back to the span where the member was written. So a service's whole job is to take a Product and return its language's answers about it. It never asks which sections are roots, because it is handed Products, not sections.

## The package shape Volar already drew

Loom is a Volar extended language, and Volar already defines what a language-service package looks like. Its own `volar-service-typescript`, `volar-service-css`, `volar-service-html`, and `volar-service-json` are each a package whose entry returns the plugins that serve one language. A Loom service is the same shape: one package per language, named `@athrio/loom-service-<id>`, whose default export is a `LanguageService`. The TypeScript service is a thin layer over `volar-service-typescript`; a service for a language Volar does not know wraps that language's own tooling instead. This is not a new package shape — it is the one Volar established.

## Found by its id

A language is found by its id, the way `tree-sitter-python` and `eslint-plugin-import` are found by theirs. The id the author activates, the package Loom imports, and the `id` the service declares are one string: `python` is `@athrio/loom-service-python`. The convention is the protocol; there is no registry to keep in step with it. Loom resolves the package from the workspace store under `.loom/`, where `loom add` installed it, never from the consumer's own dependencies.

## The host owns the runtime

A VS Code extension does not bundle the editor; it imports a `vscode` module the host provides. A Loom service follows the same rule, and the rule is what makes the whole scheme work. A service declares the Loom runtime — Effect, Volar's contracts, the service interface itself — as peer dependencies it expects from the host, and ships only its own language-specific code. The host supplies its single copy when it loads the service.

The reason is correctness before size. A service that brought its own copy of Effect would build its work against a second Effect instance, and the wiring that hands it the host's capabilities would silently miss: the capability it asks for and the one the host provides would be keyed to two different copies of the runtime, and never meet. One runtime, provided by the host, is what keeps the wiring sound — and it keeps the store small, since the heavy shared parts are never copied into it. This is the same rule by which the host provides the frame its `core`: the runtime belongs to Loom, and a package borrows it.

## Capabilities, not queries

LSP servers announce what they can do and ask the client for what they need, rather than assuming either. A Loom service asks the host, through the Effect environment, for only the capabilities its language requires. The TypeScript service takes the editor's own TypeScript compiler, so its analysis matches the user's project. The service for the frame takes the frame's diagnostics. A language that needs neither asks for neither.

One capability that used to exist is gone: a service no longer asks which sections are composition roots. That was the model leaking. The answer is the Product itself, and the Product is given. A capability is for what the host alone can provide — the compiler instance, the frame's view of a file — never a stand-in for data the de re already carries.

## In the same process, or bridged to a server

LSP isolates each language in a server process of its own. Loom keeps the isolation but inverts the default, paying for it only when it must. A service whose analysis already runs in the editor's process — TypeScript, through `volar-service-typescript` — stays in-process, with no bridge and no latency. A service for a language whose tooling is a program of its own — Python, through Pyright — starts that program and bridges to it. The choice belongs to the package, made inside the same step every service runs to build its plugins; the contract does not change between the two.

## A contract you can publish against

LSP and the VS Code API are each a contract thousands of packages depend on, and both learned the same lesson: once a contract is published, you cannot quietly change it. So Loom's service interface is a versioned contract, not an interface reshaped to fit each new language, and a service declares the version it was built for. A capability a newer host adds breaks no older package, because a service receives only what it asked for by name. The contract grows by addition, never by quiet redefinition.

## Installing, activating, degrading

`loom add <language>` installs a service into the store and records the language; the editor loads it when that language is in use. A language whose package is missing or broken takes none of the others down — it falls to syntax highlighting, the floor every section keeps, and the editor offers the command that would install it. A service loads because its language is present and in use, never eagerly, and never as a surprise from opening a file.
